Silvia Guaji Guaji, 04/04/2018, san Lorenzo de Mojos
Good afternoon, people, you all are going to watch this poor face.
kopereoopo chaonono eti imog ... imoyre joka mirorechicha .
Buenas tardes a toda la gente, Ustedes van a mirar esa pobre cara.
This afternoon, it is 4 o'clock, in 2018, it's Wednesday
jena koperei las kwatru ... te 2018... mieekuresi
Esta tarde son las cuatro, de 2018, es miercoles.
My name is Silvia Guaji Guaji, I am the daughter of late Sir Mamerto Guaji, and of Maximiliana Guaji.
nuti nkijare Silvia Guaji Guaji , ichichanu ei viya Mameetini Guaji , Maximiliana Guaji .
Me llamo Silvia Guaji Guaji, soy la hija del finado Mamerto Guaji, y de Maximiliana Guaji.
I am going to tell you all about this village of ours, San Lorenzo (De Mojos).
eti nechjisoyre te joka viowsa Sa Lorenzo .
Les voy a hablar de nuestro pueblo de aqui San Lorenzo.
The start... Jos Santos Noco Guaji started it, this man was my uncle, he still is my uncle, he still is the uncle of my father (lit. the one who has me as a child).
i... tanaekurii tnaekchooi ei i Jos Santos Noko Guaji , napiaru ei chane , napiaaricho , apiaaricho ei tkochichanu .
El comienzo lo ha comenzado Jos Santos Noco Guaji, era mi tio este hombre, todavia es mi tio, todavia es mi tio de mi padre.
He was the person responsible for this village.
El era el responsable deste pueblo.
First, the houses were made of straw, the houses.
tatiwrii eto to petirii muiji , to petyonrii .
Primero, las casas eran de paja, las casas.
And the church was made with straw, its... its thing.... its roof of the house, its roof of the house, the houses of the ancestors.
ene eto resia muiji , to ... to ta... ta... tayeerii ta... tamuigeei peti , tamuige to peti , to napenonini eno viyanovionini .
Y la iglesia era de paja, su... ,su... techo, de la casa, su techo de la casa, las casas de los Antiguos.
They took the Holy San Lorenzo, his head.
nompo ei viya Sa Lorenzo , to ichuti .
Lo llevaron el Santo san Lorenzo, su cabeza.
They left the crowd of people and they fled.
Ellos lo pusieron la multitude de gente y se huyeron.
eto = filler ? ou O de noko (to ichuti)
They fled at the times of Guayocho.
te to ... i... tyutajkompo te to ... tiempo to Wayochomurii .
Se huyeron en el tiempo de Guayocho.
Him, in times of Guayocho, the criminals killed people, fled and came here.
ei to Wayochomui eno tkopaiono tkoparekono tyutajkompo tyutekompo oni .
Aquel, en tiempo de Guayocho, los criminales mataron gente, se huyeron, vinieron aqui.
The others stayed there where it's called San Francisco.
no pomri nanospo te pjuena tkijareei San Prasisku .
Los otros se quedaron alla que se llama San Francisco.
And the others came here, those that had fled the times of Guayocho.
ene eno pomri tyutekompo te pjoka takoytajkogneei eto tiempo to Wayochomui .
Y los otros vinieron aqui lo que se han huido del tiempo de Guayocho.
They made their houses this way, they made their churches, there were (made of) straw.
enetse eto naepiakpo to napenoyooi , naepiakpo to nayeeyo resiarii , muijiricho .
Ah hicieron para sus casas, hicieron para su iglesia, estaba todavi de paja (el techo).
eto t ... muiji ... tsep... tsepaji muiji
t and tsep are false starts.
The men still had houses like that.
Eso todava era sus casas de los Seores.
They came, they scratched the buttocks of the people and put salt.
nakepripo eno naejayuttechpo nanokpo to cheve .
Vinieron ellos, y les rayaron las nalgas (de gente) y le pusieron sal.
The others crossed the river where it (the riverside) is called "borachera", that's it.
no pomriono tyanekompo te pjuena tkjare Worachera , enepo eto .
Los otros cruzaron el rio en la banda que se llama la Borrachera (nombre del monte), as era.
And they did not reach them.
Ya no los alcanzaron a ellos.
And Jos Santos Noco communicated with Spain, with the one called Saul.
ene ei i Jos Santos Noko ei tkomunikachowo te to Espaa e i tkijareei S... Sa.. . Sau... Saul
Y el Jos Santos Noco se comunic con Espaa, con Saul.
When Jos Santos Noco talked, he was still a soldier.
takeei te to echjikpo i Jos Santos Noko , sontaaricho ei .
Cuando habl el Jos santos Noko, era todava soldado.
And he ordered (it?),the one who lived in Spain brought the thing called copper.
ene iwonikpo i... imiomrikpo ei i tkowsa te to Espaa pjoka tkijareei kowre .
Y el lo mand, l mand l que vivi en Espaa este que se llamaba cobre.
Made of copper were the machetes with which they would kill, they were Herodes.
kowre eto saype nakoparesrare eno e... roresiono .
le e fait-il partie du mot ?
Cobre era el machete con que ellos mataron, ellos eran los herodes.
With that they killed the Herodes (?).
Con eso, mataron a los Herodes.
This they took from their imagination of the sword with which Herode was killing.
eto na... navepo to ... n... takuna ikoparesne i roresi
eso lo sacaron su imaginacion de la espada con que el Herode estaba matando.
They arranged the place and built a church.
en tayee tetpirikwopo nanokpo to resia
All acomodaron y construyeron la iglesia.
At three, the rooster crowed three times and the people got up.
te las tres , tom... tiyoopo mopoegiene to wrayu techpukompo
A las tres, grit tres veces el gallo, se levantaron (le gente).
They sung, they prayed, until it was daytime.
Cantaron, rezaron, hasta que ya fue aclarando (el dia).
And the ancestors were working and helping each other with their fields.
ene eno antiwono tkemtoono timkatakokonricho naesaono .
Y los antiguos trajaban y se ayudaban sus chacos.
And the woman were helping each other in their weaving.
ene eno venono te naejrure timkatakokono
Y las mujeres se ayudaban en su hilar.
They were putting them (i.e.weaving), the first ones (the ancestors) were helping each other.
hacian (los tejidos) se ayudaban los antiguos (lit. los primeros).
They were living here in our village San Lorenzo.
tkowsano te pjoka viowsa Sa Lorenzo .
Now we are super lazy, we do not meet to spin.
juiti viti vyakjispo wipo vaamutu wipo vijrurigia
Hoy dia nosotros somos flojissimos, no nos reunimos no hilamos
We do not know how to remove the seed from the cotton, we do not weave anymore.
ya no sabemos desemillar el algodon, ya no tejemos
Such were the old times, they looked for where to put their (future) boundary markers.
ene takeei to ... tyereipo natankopo to nanosoyreei eto ... manjee ... tayeonooi mojone .
as era el tiempo de atras (antes), buscaban a donde lo iban a poner sus mojones (machon que seala el limite del terreno).
The four boundary markers (of the village), they take San Lorenzo to the place of the gull (the bed of the Secure river?)
kwatrugne mojone , taveo pjoka Sa Lorenzo to tsekrereku .
los cuatro mojones, o el cuarto mojon ?
Los cuatro mojones qui limitan San Lorenzo salen en el lugar de gaviota,
They mark here next to China (name of a ranch) where they saw the river.
taveo pjoka te tnopo te China to naemuirii pjoka kjokre
confirmer prsence de glottale dans naemuiiri'i avant l'imperfectif ? pour applicatif instrumental -i'o? sinon pas de ACT. si pas de glottale pourrait tre-ri-'i DERIV-CLF'i ?
agarran aqui al lado de la China (una estancia) donde los vieron el ro
It is its name in our language.
Es su nombre en nuestro idioma.
nakoni viamririono nae... nae... naejpakgieneyore naemoyre .
Nuestros futuros nietos se van a multiplicar.

When the language is going to go away, it will spread and we don't know where it will go. There will be my nephews, my granchildren, they are going to meet and whatever, or whichever woman, they are going to say.
te to tyanaripo pjoka chojriikowo takitojiyre oypuka takijeyre ; noknojooi ncheranove , namriono nokpojkoyre ene tajpuka ... ene najpukarii psuka seno nakeyre
Cuando se vaya la palabra (el idioma), se va a desparramar y no sabemos donde va a ir. estn alla mis sobrinos, mis nietos van a encontrar y que sera, o ser la mujer (no sabemos cual), as van a decir
It is called Ichiniwa, the Spanish-speakers say, but this is not correct (this is not it).
tkjare Ichiniwa najicho no tkomeriono ene wo etina
Se llama ichiniwa dicen los castellanohablantes, pero no es.
'chinichniwa, that is to say the place of the elf, there are many jaguars.
chinichniwa o sea eto towrare to chiono , movera to chini .
'chinichniwa, o sea, el lugar de los silbacos, lugar de hartos tigres.
The name of this Ichiniwa is: 'chinichniwa.
es su nombre a este ichiniwa: 'chinichniwa.
It is that that we cross when we go to our field, where I grew up.
eto viti vianeksare vyono te visane te njuukopo
es el que que cruzamos yendo a nuestro chaco cuando yo crec
I don't know how to swim yet, with the buoy I swim.
wicho nitka nowregia , te perota nowreso .
todava no s nadar, con la camarote nado.
"acamarote" means cabin. With this and the original word "pelota", I guess "buoy" is meant.
And my parents pushed me with the leather buoy.
ene nopjup... tyopjuknu no tkochichanono te perota prumo
Y mis padres me empujaron con la camarote de cuero.
They made me cross the river with it.
Me hicieron cruzar el rio con este.
It was like this long ago, then they have been thinking about it.
As era hace tiempo, despus lo pensaron.
And they named it San Lorenzo de Mojos.
ene naechjisopo to tkijarepo to SaLorenzo Tmojoro .
As lo nombraron San Lorenzo de Mojos.
My language, me as a woman, this foreign woman is thinking about it, making the most of the customs of our village.
eto nechjiriiwo nuti , nuti seno , psuka seno powsajekgiene ssopei skopneriiji to tayeerepi pjoka viowsa viti .
Mi idioma de mi, yo como mujer, esta Seora estrangera lo esta pensando aprovechandolo las costumbres de nuestro pueblo.
We don't think (have in our heart), we don't write all the we see when there is daylight (all that one can see), each afternoon.
wo wako... wakowsamreji wo viajkunacha to tajpuka to ... timokre to tjarainvepo , koperenovepo .
tajarinvepo, koperenovepo. En fait, koperenovepo et sa traduc tait initialement dans la phrase suivante, mais a ne collait pas lintonation.
pas sre de l'analyse de kowsamre, peut-tre kowo 'baarse' ni de sa traduc (dico NT tener en el corazon), ni traduc de ajkuna ou yajkuna (dico NT "sacar foto")
No pensamos, no escribemos todo lo que vemos cuando ya aclara el da (lo que se ve), cada tarde.
There is nothing... no one that comes ( =nobody cares).
No hay nada o quin viene (no le importa a nadie).
Now she comes from far to visit us.
Ahora ella viene de lejos a visitarnos.
She takes the traditions of our village, the start of our village.
svejno eto tayeerepi joka viowsa , tanaekrupi joka viowsa
Elle lleva los costumbres de nuestro pueblo, su principio de nuestro pueblo
Well, these are all my words.
on entend juste ka et pas pjoka
Thanks and see you later, I'll be back (lit. I'm already going).
Gracias y hasta luego, vuelvo (lit. ya me estoy yendo).
